			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Bill's got several good points. Parents are raising their children. They need to raise them right. In that sense, race is of no consequence.
<br />

<br />
What I get loud and clear from his message is this
<br />

<br />
Civil rights leaders did not die for this generation to be killing each other, committing crimes and wasting a perfectly good education opportunity. Don't tell me black kids in the ghetto can't go to college, they have more scholarships available than my white children do. Don't believe me? Try to find a scholarship specifically for whites only. You won't find any, but there are MANY scholarships available to minorities only.
<br />
The culture that he refers to is the ghetto culture, if you will. Where for the most part people do not see beyond their face and aren't taking advantage of educational opportunities.
<br />
White people have ghettos too. There are as many, if not more, ignorant while folk doing the same damn thing. Bill's cause isn't about white people. so his statements are directed towards the black community.
<br />

<br />
Parents need to instill the importance of education in their children at an early age. Otherwise, they'll miss the opportunities that black folk would not have had 50 years ago. His message is clear ... The world has changed and now it's time for the economically challenged minorities to make some changes too. It's about changing the culture and getting the message across that there is more to this world that public housing, welfare or minimum wage jobs and prison.
<br />
I applaud Bill for speaking to minorities. Sometimes you have to creatively word your message to inspire debate. Bill's approach will definately spark the attention he intended his statements to get.
<br />
He did not shoot from the hip here, he knew exactly what he was saying.
<br />

<br />
Sev<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
